04325nam a22005415i 9781928096719DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97819280967197 a10.1515/97819280967192doi  a(DE-B1597)656425  a(OCoLC)1026802307  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aTK5105.875.I57bH36 2016 7aPOL0120002bisacsh04a004.72231 aHampson, Fen Osler, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLook Who's Watching, Revised Edition :bSurveillance, Treachery and Trust Online /cFen Osler Hampson, Eric Jardine. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource :b10 tables, 42 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tAcronyms & Initialisms -- tSex, Spies and the Internet -- tAn Ecosystem Based on Trust -- tA World Online — Economics, Innovation and the Internet of Things -- tBig Brother in the Internet Age -- tOne or Many, Internet or Fragnet? -- tCrime, Punishment and the Deep Dark Web -- tCyberwarfare in the Twenty-first Century -- tInternet Haves and Have-Nots -- tA Web of Trust: Toward a Safe, Secure, Reliable and Open Internet -- tNotes -- tAppendix -- tAfterword -- tIndex -- tAbout the Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Internet ecosystem is held together by a surprisingly intangible glue — trust. To meet its full potential, users need to trust that the Internet works reliably and efficiently when providing them with the information they are seeking, while also being secure, private and safe. When trust in the Internet wanes, the network’s stock of “digital social capital” falls and users begin to alter their online behaviour. These often subtle changes in behaviour tend to be collectively highly maladaptive, hindering the economic, developmental and innovative potential of the globe-spanning network of networks. Look Who’s Watching: Surveillance, Treachery and Trust Online confirms in vivid detail that the trust placed by users in the Internet is increasingly misplaced. Edward Snowden’s revelations that the United States National Security Agency and other government agencies are spying on Internet users, the proliferation of cybercrime and the growing commodification of user data and regulatory changes — which threaten to fragment the system — are all rapidly eroding the confidence users have in the Internet ecosystem. Based on a combination of illustrative anecdotal evidence and analysis of new survey data, Look Who’s Watching clearly demonstrates why trust matters, how it is being eroded and how, with care and deliberate policy action, the essential glue of the Internet can be restored.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aInternet governance. 0aInternetxSecurity measures. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh1 aJardine, Eric, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978192809671940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781928096719423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781928096719/original  a978-3-11-127365-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-127619-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles